              <h2>What is a mortgage?</h2>
              <p>
                A mortgage is a loan secured by real estate. You borrow money
                from a lender to buy (or refinance) a property, and the property
                itself serves as collateral. If you stop making payments, the
                lender can foreclose and sell the home to recover what you owe.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <strong>Standard fixed‑rate mortgage payment formula</strong
                ><br />
                Monthly payment \(M\) for loan amount \(L\), monthly interest
                rate \(r\), and number of payments \(n\):<br />
                \[ M = L \cdot \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]
              </div>

              <h3>Key parts of a typical mortgage payment</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Principal</strong> – the amount you borrowed and still
                  owe.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest</strong> – the cost of borrowing, based on
                  your interest rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Property taxes</strong> – often collected monthly and
                  paid by your lender once or twice a year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Homeowners insurance</strong> – protects against
                  damage and liability.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PMI or mortgage insurance</strong> – required on many
                  loans with &lt;20% down.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>HOA dues</strong> – if your property is in a
                  homeowners association.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How lenders decide how much you can borrow</h2>
              <p>
                Lenders look at your credit, income, debts, and savings. Two of
                the most important metrics are your
                <strong>debt‑to‑income (DTI) ratios</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Front‑end DTI</strong>: housing costs ÷ gross monthly
                  income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Back‑end DTI</strong>: housing + other monthly debts ÷
                  gross monthly income.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <strong>Example – front‑end DTI</strong><br />
                If a lender allows 28% for housing and you earn $6,000/month:<br />
                Max housing payment ≈ \( 6{,}000 \times 0.28 = 1{,}680 \) per
                month.
              </div>

              <p>
                Our
